            "body": "Here is an example config to reproduce:\r\n\r\n```lua\r\n-- ./init.lua\r\n\r\nvim.pack.add({\r\n\t\"https://github.com/nvim-lua/plenary.nvim\",\r\n\t\"https://github.com/nvim-neotest/nvim-nio\",\r\n\t\"https://github.com/nvim-neotest/neotest\",\r\n\t\"https://github.com/nvim-neotest/neotest-plenary\",\r\n})\r\n\r\nrequire(\"neotest\").setup({\r\n\tadapters = {\r\n\t\trequire(\"neotest-plenary\"),\r\n\t},\r\n})\r\n\r\n-- ./tests/foo_spec.lua\r\n\r\ndescribe(\"foo\", function()\r\n\tit(\"bar\", function()\r\n\t\tassert.True(1 == 2)\r\n\tend)\r\nend)\r\n```\r\n\r\n1. Run `nvim -u init.lua tests/foo_spec.lua` (tested with current master, 17d1260)\r\n2. Put cursor to the start of `assert`\r\n3. Run `:lua require\"neotest\".run.run()` \r\n\r\nIf it doesn't straight up crash, it will spew out lots of error messages.\r\n\r\nP.S. it doesn't have to be lua test (i found it originally with go), the issue triggers anytime you open neotest floating output window.",
